    "created_at": "2017-02-24T19:00:42Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-02-24T19:10:54Z",
    "body": "I think I have to clarify that I was talking about moving window between spaces or desktops, not different physical displays. While searching on internet I found that moving windows between desktops is a part of private API. \r\n\r\nHowever It's possible to specify a window behavior to move it to active space:\r\n\r\n`window.collectionBehavior |= NSWindowCollectionBehaviorMoveToActiveSpace;`\r\n\r\n> NSWindowCollectionBehaviorMoveToActiveSpace\r\n>Making the window active does not cause a space switch; the window switches to the active space.\r\n\r\nAnother option that seems to be already implemented:\r\n\r\n> NSWindowCollectionBehaviorCanJoinAllSpaces\r\n>The window appears in all spaces. The menu bar behaves this way.\r\n\r\nReference: https://github.com/electron/electron/blob/1dd37eaab71a8a64d1f68fb88622ac3e2a31bc4a/atom/browser/native_window_mac.mm#L1269\r\n\r\nSo I guess a combination of both should give a desired effect.\r\n\r\nIt's really trivial fix to set an additional flag to move window to active space to avoid space switch when it becomes active, i.e:\r\n\r\n```cpp\r\nvoid NativeWindowMac::SetMoveToActiveSpace(bool enabled) {\r\n  SetCollectionBehavior(enabled, NSWindowCollectionBehaviorMoveToActiveSpace);\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nI don't really understand the point of `NSWindowCollectionBehaviorCanJoinAllSpaces` without `NSWindowCollectionBehaviorMoveToActiveSpace`, but maybe there are use cases I am not aware of.."
  },
